<font color="#FF0000">DON'T FEEL GUILTY</font><br>
<tt>Fri Nov 29 17:42:46 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
For heaven's sake, don't feel guilty about not having served in Vietnam, or gone into the service during that era.  I enlisted in the Air Force when I found that being drafted was inevitable.  I wanted a choice as to what I did.  I ended up extending a 4-year enlistment to go to DaNang in the Aerospace Rescue &amp; Recovery Service.  But very soon after getting over there, I began working on leaving.  I received an early out off my extention to go back to school, so I served 8 months in-country.  <br><br>
While there, I read a book entitled &quot;Our Own Worst Enemy.&quot;  I don't know the author, but it detailed the corruption that was so prevalent during that era and place.  It and other experiences convinced me that the best thing would be to get out as soon as possible.  <br><br>
I did, and I'm still here.  You're still here too.  That's the important part.  What we now have to do is continue these dialogs, and work to understand what happened, why it happened, the decisions made, how they have affected us, and what we can do, and cannot do, in the future.  <br><br>
Feeling guilty does nothing constructive.  It can only make you miserable, and that's not appropriate.  Especially so during this holiday season.  Enjoy!<br><br>

